  "prompt": "How does magnesium oxide react with water?",
  "response": "Magnesium oxide (MgO) reacts with water to form magnesium hydroxide (Mg(OH)\u2082). The reaction is relatively simple and can be represented by the following chemical equation:\n\n\\[ \\text{MgO (s)} + \\text{H}_2\\text{O (l)} \\rightarrow \\text{Mg(OH)}_2 \\text{ (s)} \\]\n\nIn this reaction, solid magnesium oxide combines with liquid water to produce solid magnesium hydroxide. This reaction is an example of a metal oxide reacting with water to form a hydroxide.\n\nMagnesium hydroxide is sparingly soluble in water, which means that while some of it will dissolve, a significant portion will remain as solid particles. The result is a suspension rather than a true solution. Magnesium hydroxide is commonly known as milk of magnesia and is used in various applications, including as an antacid and a laxative.",
